D-f and d-u, the two questions about disk space.

There are two completely different questions you can ask about disk space, and they have two completely different tools. The first question is, how much space is on my filesystems? That is answered by d-f, short for disk free. It shows usage per mounted filesystem: the total size, the used space, the space still available, the percentage used, and where each filesystem is mounted. Add dash h for human-readable sizes and dash capital-t to also show the filesystem type.

D-f has two surprises worth flagging. The first is the root reserve: on e-x-t-four, five percent of the filesystem is reserved for root by default, so when d-f says ninety-five percent used, an ordinary user may already be unable to write, even though there appears to be space; you can lower that reserve with a tuning command. The second surprise is that you can run out of inodes before you run out of bytes. Each file consumes one inode, and the number of inodes is fixed when the filesystem is created, so a flood of tiny files can exhaust them while bytes remain free. The d-f command with dash i reveals inode usage, and a no-space-left error while bytes are still available is the tell-tale sign.

The second question is, what is using the space inside this directory? That is answered by d-u, disk usage, which walks a directory tree and reports how much space each item takes. The most useful forms give a single human-readable summary of a whole tree, or a one-level-deep breakdown to find the big subdirectories. The killer combination for finding what is eating your disk is to summarise each item in a directory, pipe it through sort with the human-numeric flag, and look at the largest at the bottom. One last subtlety: occasionally d-f reports the disk full while d-u shows far less in use; the classic cause is a deleted-but-still-open file, where a process still holds a removed file open, so its space is not freed and not counted until that process closes it or restarts.
